XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This single-vehicle crash occurred in a rural area on a three-lane roadway with curves and variable grades. In the area of the crash, the westbound roadway was wet, curves right and had a downhill grade of seven percent with a posted speed limit of 65 mph (104 kph). The eastbound roadway consists of 2 lanes. The crash occurred during darkness while it was raining heavily.
Vehicle one (V1), a 2000 Chevrolet Malibu, was westbound when it began to fishtail on the wet roadway. V1 slid to the right in a clockwise rotation and departed the right road edge. The left side struck a metal reflector post. The front, left and back then struck an embankment while V1 continue to rotate. The front of V1 then struck the ditch at the bottom of the embankment. V1 came to rest on the embankment facing east and was towed due to damage.
The driver of V1, a seventeen-year- old male, was traveling with a thirty-five-year-old female and a fifteen-year-old female. They were on their way home from a community meeting. This driver was healthy, well rested and comfortable with his vehicle, route and passengers. He stated that he steered right in a futile attempt to regain control of the vehicle.
The critical pre-crash event was coded as: "this vehicle control loss due to traveling too fast for conditions." The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event was coded as: "driver related factor; too fast for conditions (heavy rain/wet roads)."
